### Infrastructure Explanation

1. Why additional elements?
- Load Balancer (HAproxy): Added to distribute incoming traffic across multiple servers to prevent overloading a single server and to provide high availability.
- Second Server: Added to eliminate the single point of failure at the server level.
- Database Cluster (Primary-Replica): Added to ensure data redundancy and improve read performance.

2. Load Balancer Algorithm (Round Robin):
This algorithm distributes requests sequentially across the pool of available servers. Each server takes a turn in a circular order, ensuring an even distribution of work.

3. Active-Active vs Active-Passive:
- Active-Active: All servers/load balancers are working simultaneously to handle traffic.
- Active-Passive: Only one server/load balancer is active at a time; the "passive" one stays on standby and only takes over if the "active" one fails.

4. Database Primary-Replica (Master-Slave) Cluster:
- Primary (Master): Handles all "Write" operations (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE). It is the source of truth.
- Replica (Slave): Synchronizes with the Primary and handles "Read" operations (SELECT). This reduces the load on the Master.

5. Difference between Primary and Replica:
- The Application sends all data-changing requests to the Primary node.
- The Application can pull data from the Replica node to speed up response times for users.

### Issues with this Infrastructure

- SPOF (Single Point of Failure): The Load Balancer itself is now a SPOF. If HAproxy fails, the whole system is unreachable.
- Security Issues: No Firewall is configured to block malicious traffic, and no HTTPS is used (data is sent in clear text).
- No Monitoring: We cannot see the health of the servers or the status of the services in real-time.
